    <descript>
      <abstract>This layer contains zoning information for Fairfax County, Virginia.  This includes, but is not limited to the portrayal of polygonal features that depict the boundary of zones.  This layer was initially developed as a digital copy of the ink-on-mylar property maps maintained by the County since the early 1960s.</abstract>
      <purpose>This layer was created to depict zones created by Board of Supervisors of the County of Fairfax.  Primary purpose of this data is the graphic portrayal of zoned land and their spatial relationships throughout Fairfax County.</purpose>
    </descript>

  <dataqual>
    <attracc>
      <attraccr>The draw symbol attribute was checked by plotting the features on the standard map product and ensuring the features appeared and were drawn correctly.  The zoning code was checked by comparing annotation to draw symbol for zoning type.</attraccr>
    </attracc>
    <logic>Segments making up the outer and inner boundaries of a polygon tie end-to-end to completely enclose the area.  No duplicate features exist.  Intersecting lines are separated into individual line segments at the point of intersection.  All nodes are represented by a single coordinate pair, which indicates the beginning or end of a line segment.  Logical consistency was tested by visual inspection and automated quality control procedures.</logic>
    <complete>Continually being updated. Errors being corrected as they are found. QC of data being done prior to updates.  Data is updated as documents are received in the GIS office.</complete>

      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Data copied from the CD obtained from Fairfax County, VA 2007.
Mount mylar on digitizer and register. Get Root Mean Square (RMS) better than 3.5 feet. Digitize tile neatline. THE CONTACT AND THE PROCESS DATE (1997-1999) IS THE SAME FOR ALL THE PROCESS STEPS IN THE DATA QUALITY INFORMATION SECTION.</procdesc>
        <srcused>MYLAR (THE SOURCE CITATION INFORMATION IS THE SAME FOR ALL THE SOURCE CITATION ABBR. LISTED IN THIS SECTION)</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1999</procdate>
        <srcprod>MOUNTED MYLAR</srcprod>
        <proccont>
          <cntinfo>
            <cntorgp>
              <cntorg>Fairfax County GIS and Mapping Services</cntorg>
            </cntorgp>
            <cntpos>Database Administrator</cntpos>
            <cntaddr>
              <addrtype>mailing and physical address</addrtype>
              <address>12000 Government Center Pw. Suite 117</address>
              <city>Fairfax</city>
              <state>VA</state>
              <postal>22035</postal>
              <country>USA</country>
            </cntaddr>
            <cntvoice>(703)-324-2712</cntvoice>
            <cntfax>(703)-324-3937</cntfax>
            <cntemail>gis.helpq@fairfaxcounty.gov</cntemail>
          </cntinfo>
        </proccont>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Digitize all data from source mylar. Overlay street name mylar. Capture all street names and additional line work.</procdesc>
        <srcused>MOUNTED MYLAR</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>DIGITIZED DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Code linework so it will be the proper entity on the map. Code annotation so that each text will go into the proper layer.</procdesc>
        <srcused>DIGITIZED DATA</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CODED DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Perform on screen best fit of the data using planimetric data as a reference. Keep individual zoning distortion to a minimum. Do block adjustment associated with parcel data.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CODED DATA</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>ADJUSTED DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Edgematch data with surrounding tiles. Lines must be snapped. Polygon attribution must be identical. Deleted problems are logged, researched and corrected.</procdesc>
        <srcused>ADJUSTED DATA</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>EDGEMATCHED DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Automated data cleanup. This  includes removing overshoots and undershoots, breaking all lines at intersecting lines and rotating annotation with 15 feet at a line to the same angle as the line.</procdesc>
        <srcused>EDGEMATCHED DATA</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CLEANED DATA  / FIRST PASS</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Line attribution and polygon building. Code linework correctly for map display. Code polygon correctly so that the data goes into the correct region subclass in ArcInfo.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CLEANED DATA  / FIRST PASS</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>DATA READY FOR TRANSLATION</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Second pass of automated data cleanup. This is to be sure editor did not introduce any new errors.</procdesc>
        <srcused>DATA READY FOR TRANSLATION</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CLEANED DATA  / SECOND PASS</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>First quality check of digital data. Each file was plotted and checked for accuracy by overlaying plotted digital data on mylar sources. All interior data and data up to one inch outside the neatline is checked.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CLEANED DATA  / SECOND PASS</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>QC DATA / FIRST PASS</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Translation from APS to ArcInfo. Regions are built and the data is translated.</procdesc>
        <srcused>QC DATA / FIRST PASS</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>ARCINFO COVERAGE</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Second quality check. ArcInfo data was plotted and overlaid on source mylars to review the overall quality and consistency. If changes are needed the files are fixed in APS, retranslated and replotted.</procdesc>
        <srcused>ARCINFO COVERAGE</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>QC ARCINFO COVERAGE</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Zoning documents are received in the GIS and Mapping Services office. The document is reviewed to determine the zone that has been granted.  This zone polygon is then taken from the zone case data and added to the zoning data as a granted zone.</procdesc>
        <srcused>ZONING DOCUMENT</srcused>
        <procdate>2000-2004</procdate>
        <srcprod>REVIEW ZONING DOCUMENT</srcprod>
        <srcprod>EXTRACT ZONING DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Composite data is merged into extracted data. Topology is built and data is attributed and annotation is constructed. Check is preformed for topology and label errors. Quality control program is run by GIS technicians. Data is submitted for final review and acceptance.</procdesc>
        <srcused>EXTRACT ZONING DATA</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>FINAL DRAFT DIGITAL ZONING DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Quality control procedures are performed by reviewer including visual inspection, attribute check, and validity check. If no errors are found data is committed back through GATE to the database. If errors are found returned to GIS technician for corrections.</procdesc>
        <srcused>FINAL DRAFT DIGITAL ZONING DATA</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>FINAL ACCEPTED ZONING DATA</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Metadata imported.</procdesc>
        <srcused>C:\DOCUME~1\stulad\LOCALS~1\Temp\xml1497.tmp</srcused>
        <procdate/>
      </procstep>

    <overview>
      <eaover>These layers contains polygons, lines, and annotation. Each zoning polygon feature contains the zoning code and in the case of zoning case polygon contains the case number and the status of the zoning case.  Also the polygons contain the draw symbol used to portray the zoning classification on the zoning maps.</eaover>
